Realized
Aspen Pipeline II





  Status: Realized
  Headquarters: Houston, TX

  Aspen Pipeline II was formed in January 2008 to invest in the Odessa Fuels project, a pipeline in West Texas to gather and deliver high nitrogen content natural gas to customers capable of directly burning the gas without nitrogen removal. The Odessa Fuels project was sold to DCP Midstream in February 2012. Aspen Pipeline II continues to own an interest in Robbins Community Power, a 50 MW biomass power plant in Illinois.
  



Active
Ceritas Energy II





  Status: Active
  Headquarters: Houston, TX
www.ceritasgroup.com

  ESC and Quantum Energy Partners established Ceritas II in February 2008 to pursue midstream opportunities. Ceritas II is developing natural gas gathering systems in the Piceance Basin in western Colorado and in the Marcellus Shale play in central Pennsylvania. Ceritas II has also formed a joint venture with a leading industry technology provider to pursue opportunities to process natural gas liquids from the CO2 recycle stream in CO2 flood projects. The joint venture currently has one plant operating in the Permian Basin.
  



Realized
Frontier Midstream





  Status: Realized
  Headquarters: Tulsa, OK
www.frontierenergyllc.com

  Frontier Midstream was formed in March 2008 with a strategy of acquiring and/or building greenfield midstream development projects, initially located in the Fayetteville Shale, Marcellus Shale, Permian Basin and the Mid-Continent area. Frontier was led by the previous President & CEO and several other management team members of Frontier Field Services (a Fund II/III company) Frontier acquired and/or constructed four gathering systems in the Fayetteville Shale in Arkansas and a gas plant and gathering system in the Granite Wash play of the Texas Panhandle. In April 2011, the Company sold all of its assets to Crestwood Midstream Partners.
  



Realized
Hoover Energy Partners





  Status: Realized
  Headquarters: Houston, TX
www.hooverenergy.com

  Hoover Energy Partners ("Hoover") operated a gas gathering and treating system in Pecos County, as well as an associated gas gathering and water transportation and disposal system in Reeves County, Texas. Hoover also operated its Pecos Crossing Pipeline, a 24-mile 12" crude oil gathering and transportation system that serves producers throughout the southern Delaware Permian Basin.  Hoover's assets were sold to Regency Energy Partners in February 2014.
  



Realized
Laser Midstream II





  Status: Realized
  Headquarters: Houston, TX
www.lasernortheast.com

  In November 2007, Laser II was formed to pursue opportunities in the midstream gas business with a primary focus on acquiring and expanding under-utilized systems in mature areas. Laser II's primary project was a greenfield Marcellus Shale gathering project in Susquehanna County, PA.  In July 2010, Laser Northeast (the Susquehanna project) was sold to Delphi Midstream Partners.  Laser II management continues to operate a joint venture to identify and activate projects associated with several acquired idle crude pipelines primarily located in Texas and Louisiana.
  



Realized
Stonehenge Energy Resources





  Status: Realized
  Headquarters: Denver, CO
www.stonehengeenergy.com

  In November 2007, Stonehenge was formed to focus on the design, construction and operation of new-build gas pipelines and treating projects. In December 2009, the Company formed Keystone Midstream Services, a joint venture with Rex Energy, to build a Marcellus Shale gathering system and gas processing plants in Butler County, PA. The first plant was completed in December 2010 and the second plant in June 2012. Stonehenge sold its interests in Keystone Midstream Services to MarkWest Energy Partners in May 2012.
  



Realized
Texas Energy Midstream





  Status: Realized
  Headquarters: Dallas, TX
  
  In July 2008, Texas Energy Midstream was formed to acquire and develop midstream assets with organic growth opportunities in Texas, beginning in the Barnett Shale. The company constructed and operated a gathering system and compression facility in Tarrant County, Texas, in the heart of the Barnett Shale. In September 2014, a subsidiary of Summit Midstream Partners LP acquired TEM’s Barnett Shale assets.
  



Realized
TransEdge Energy





  Status: Realized
  Headquarters: Houston, TX
www.transedge-energy.com

  In July 2007, TransEdge Energy was formed to pursue opportunities primarily in the refined products pipeline and terminal sectors. Owner of refined products and propane distribution assets in New Hampshire, TransEdge Energy was sold to Stone Road Energy in October 2014.
  



Realized
Tristate Midstream





  Status: Realized
  Headquarters: Denton, TX
www.tsmidstream.com

  Established in November 2007, Tristate Midstream was a midstream natural gas gathering company focused on the acquisition and construction of gathering systems and processing facilities in Texas, Louisiana and Arkansas. The Company's first acquisition was a gas gathering and compression system in Red River Parish, Louisiana, which was expanded and eventually sold to Energy Transfer Partners in March 2010. In November 2011 the Company sold its remaining gathering and compression assets in Sabine Parish, Louisiana, to Crestwood Midstream Partners.
  



Realized
Velocity Midstream Partners





  Status: Realized
  Headquarters: Tulsa, OK
www.velocitymidstream.com

  Velocity Midstream was established in November 2008 with an initial focus to acquire, build and develop midstream assets with organic growth opportunities in the Continental United States.  In July 2009, the Company acquired certain East Texas gas gathering assets from Berry Petroleum Company and subsequently sold those assets in November 2010.  Velocity then constructed an Eagle Ford Shale condensate gathering and storage system in South Texas, which was sold to Plains All American Pipeline LP in November 2011.
  





